Central Park: Sailboat Pond, with Fifth Avenue from 73rd to 74th
Streets in the background.

P. L. Sperr.

709137f-a.text:
Fifth Ave., east side, north from and including East 73rd Street. The building on the right is No. 920 Fifth Ave. and is at the S.E. corner of 73rd Street.
July 29, 1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Art Project.

709138f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, east side, north from E. 73rd to 74th Streets, showing private dwellings facing Central Park and which constitute a portion of Manhattan's "Gold Coast". At the extreme left is a 12 story apartment house (No. 927 Fifth Avenue, at the S.E. corner of 74th Street) upon the site of the former A.D. Pell home. Owners of the other structures are (or were) J.A. Simpson, M. W. Terrell (subsequently by Reed L. Carr), Georgia W. Warren, Eliza Guggenheimer  and Geo. W. Quintard.

View 2 and 3 show only the latter feature. The white building adjoining same was remodelled for apartment use and a report to that effect carried in the New York Times of November 30, 1937. Chas. S. Guggenheimer of the law firm of Guggenheimer, Untermeyer and Marshall was the former occupant.
August 15, 1939.
View 2: July 21, 1937
View 3: April 23, 1938.

P. L. Sperr.

709139f-a.text:
922 to 926 Fifth Avenue, at N.E. corner of 73rd Street.
June 1925.
According to the New York Times of November 30, 1937, the Charles S. Guggenheimer home (No. 923) will be remodelled for apartment use. This edifice is the ornamented 5-story structure that adjoins the corner.
